-- Factbox: Asian stocks on the move after Japan quake
-- 
-- Mon Mar 14, 2011 6:15am EDT
-- http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/03/14/us-japan-asia-stocks-idUSTRE72D2SI20110314

 

 (Reuters) - Shares in several Asian companies tumbled on Monday after the massive earthquake and tsunami in Japan that likely killed more than 10,000 people. 

 While manufacturers and automakers in Japan fell, construction stocks rose on expectations of increased demand. Coal and steel shares elsewhere also gained on anticipated demand in Japan. Following is a roundup of the stocks impacted by Friday's earthquake, which forced Japanese automakers, electronics firms and oil refiners to shut key factories. Stock moves as of 0500 GMT (1 a.m. ET). Japan SONY CORP FALLS 9 PCT Shares in Sony fell after the company suspended production at eight plants in the affected region. TOYOTAunable to inspect factories in the worst-affected areas. Toyota builds 38 percent of its vehicles in Japan. NISSAN DOWN 10.5 PCT Japan and will not restart on Monday. Nissan manufactures 22 percent of its vehicles in Japan. HONDA DOWN 7.7 PCT the southern island of Kyushu. Honda makes 24 percent of its cars in Japan. UNTRADED ON GLUT OF SELL ORDERS Tokyo Electric Power was untraded on a glut of sell orders 200 times the number of bids. Japan's biggest utility has battled to cool damaged reactors at its Fukushima plant. CONSTRUCTION SHARES GAIN The construction stock price index rose 6.8 percent on expectations of booming orders to rebuild northeastern Japan. ** General contractor Kajima Corp up 23.1 percent. ** Hazama Corp up 41.1 percent. ** Home builder Misawa Homes up 19.1 percent ** Hitachi Construction Machinery Co up 1 percent. AUSTRALIA Shares of Australia-listed uranium miners, some of the world's biggest, tumbled as Japan's struggle to prevent a catastrophe at earthquake-damaged nuclear power generators raised questions about the industry's future. ** Energy Resources of Australia, a unit of global miner Rio Tinto, was down 11.7 percent. ** Paladin lost 16.3 percent. ** Silex Systems, which pioneers technology for uranium enrichment for nuclear use, was down 8.9 percent. Insurers fell as investors expected the quake to further harden reinsurance costs. ** Insurance Australia Group down 2.9 percent. ** Suncorp falls 1.8 percent. ** QBE Insurance down 1.3 percent. BLUESCOPE STEEL UP 7.8 PERCENT The stock rose on expectations that Japan may be forced to import finished steel products as part of its rebuilding efforts. OneSteel rose 1.7 percent. CHINA Shares in Chinese power equipment companies fell in Hong Kong as the nuclear leakage in Japan sparked worries it could slow efforts in the country to build more nuclear power stations. Dongfang Electric Corp The company, which has the most exposure in the sector among equipment makers, lost 8.9 percent in Hong Kong and 5.7 percent in Shanghai. The company has a backlog of nuclear equipment orders exceeding 40 billion yuan as of 2010-end, said Yuanta analyst Wendy Wang, accounting for 31 percent of the company's expected backlog. HARBIN POWER EQUIPMENT CO LTD DOWN 3.8 PCT The company has been increasing its exposure in the nuclear-power sector. Peer Shanghai Electric lost 7.2 percent. TAIWAN AU Optronics, the world's No.4 flat-panel maker, was down 2.6 percent. The company's chairman said he sees limited impact on AU's facility in Japan, though he was worried the quake would affect the supply chain. THAILAND MCS Steel up 3.5 pct The stock gained after the company said its operations in Japan had very little impact from the earthquake. SINGAPORE STRAITS ASIA RESOURCES UP 2.6 PCT Shares of the coal miner rose on expectations that Japanese demand for coal will rise in the wake of the earthquake. SOUTH KOREA Seoul shares reversed earlier losses to turn positive as tech and auto exporters jumped on production disruptions in Japan. ** Samsung Electronics rose 3.7 percent, Hyundai Motor up 1.4 percent. ** POSCO, the world's No.3 steelmaker, rallied 8 percent. Hyundai Steel surged 8 percent. ** State-run Korea Electric Power Corp (KEPCO) fell 3.9 percent. ** Doosan Heavy Industries & Construction Co slid 13 percent. INDONESIA Bumi resources UP 3.3 PCT Asia's largest thermal coal producer expects demand and prices to rise, helped by Japan's rebuilding efforts and substitution of nuclear power with coal power. Japan buyers accounted for about 21 percent of the company's 2010 coal sales. Indo Tambangraya Megah UP 5.1 PCT